Test file: src/claim-office.spec.ts
Failing test: "should return premium 65 G for 3 runes — 60 G block base + 5 G fee"
Expected behavior: 3 runes = 60 G block premium + 5 fee = 65 G
Current error: Expected 65, Received 80 (3 × 25 + 5)
Implementation file: src/claim-office.ts

Current implementation:
```typescript
const KNOWN_TYPES = ["sword", "amulet", "staff", "potion", "rune", "moonstone"];

function validateItemTypes(items: any[]): void {
  for (const item of items) {
    if (!KNOWN_TYPES.includes(item.type)) {
      throw new Error(`Unknown item type: ${item.type}`);
    }
  }
}

const PROCESSING_FEE = 5;

const BASE_PREMIUMS: Record<string, number> = {
  sword: 100,
  amulet: 60,
  staff: 80,
  potion: 40,
  rune: 25,
};

function basePremium(item: any): number {
  return BASE_PREMIUMS[item.type] ?? 0;
}

export function claimOffice(input: any): unknown {
  const results = [];
  for (const step of input.steps) {
    validateItemTypes(step.items);
    let premium = PROCESSING_FEE;
    for (const item of step.items) {
      premium += basePremium(item);
    }
    results.push({ premium });
  }
  return { results };
}
```

Rules for component block pricing:
- Components are "rune" and "moonstone" types
- A block of exactly 3 alike components has a special base premium of 60 G (instead of 3 × 25 = 75)
- "Alike" means exactly the same type (3 runes = block, 2 runes + 1 moonstone = NOT a block)
- Block requires exactly 3: 4 runes = 4 × 25 = 100 (no block)

For now, just make this test pass. The minimal approach: when computing premiums, check if there are exactly 3 components of the same type and use 60 G instead of 75 G.

EXPERIMENT MODE: Run autonomously, proceed to Refactor after completion.

